You see this card a lot during the draft since it's a common, but I tend to find that it's hard to take unless you are in a very specific type of deck. You really want to be planning to make specific very powerful functions, increasing the numbers of your functions via sentient form/fine tuning, have ways to benefit from statuses and bug barrage, or assembling an infinite using the energy gain alongside goto usually. Those situations can definitely come up, and this card is very powerful in them, but you have to be very careful about when you are adding it to your deck, as it's pretty atrocious in most of act 1/2, since it tends to hurt the first cycle through your deck, and is a weak draw in most short hallway fights. It's even a skill for gremlin nob, and very bad into tri-sentries as a source of more dazes. One of the better ways to mitigate these issues is by finding strong frontloaded mitigation from relics like the boat relics, and incense burner.

As energy generation it doesn't do anything the first time you play it or the resulting function, and it even puts 2 dazes into your draw pile while doing that, putting you down 1 card overall, and making it harder to get to your first reshuffle. That's a massive downside, especially for the classic "jam as many random functions together as you can and reshuffle" playstyle that tends to be very dominant on automaton. You even have turbo available on the same character, which gives 2 energy and puts 1 status into your discard pile instead, so buggy mess to me feels like it's largely meant to be played in decks trying to assemble an infinite or decks that want to be abusing the status synergies. I haven't really found going infinite to be necessary on automaton, but this is one of the better ways to do it, though I think it gets overshadowed by the random function deck. Upgrade helps it generate energy the first time, but does nothing else, so fairly weak.
Mallet makes this much better. Bronze idol and gelatinous cube can help synergize with the dazes.
